language Essence 1.3

$ Social Golfers Problem — Formulation 3: Function to Partitions
$
$ Domain:  function (total) int(1..w) --> partition (regular, numParts g, partSize s) from Golfers
$
$ Information carried by the domain:
$   - Totality: every week in 1..w is mapped to a partition
$   - Each partition has g groups of size s, covering all golfers
$   - Disjointness and coverage: partition semantics
$   - Weeks are explicitly indexed via function application
$
$ Explicit constraints needed:
$   - Pairing constraint
$
$ Compared to Formulation 1 (set of partitions):
$   - Weeks are indexed by int(1..w), similar to the sequence formulation.
$   - The function domain adds totality as a guarantee (every week has a schedule).
$   - Function injectivity could optionally be used to ensure distinct weeks,
$     but we use total here to stay general.

given w, g, s : int(1..)

letting nGolfers be g * s
letting Golfers be new type of size nGolfers

find sched : function (total) int(1..w) --> partition (regular, numParts g, partSize s) from Golfers

$ Pairing constraint
such that
    forAll p1 : Golfers .
        forAll p2 : Golfers .
            p1 != p2 ->
            (sum i : int(1..w) .
                sum part in parts(sched(i)) .
                    toInt(p1 in part /\ p2 in part)
            ) <= 1
